text:
It's genetic!!!!!
The vast number of genes associated with autism primarily fall into three key functional areas in the brain:
1. Synaptic Function: Many high-risk autism genes are involved in how neurons communicate with each other across synapses. This includes genes involved in shaping the "wiring" of the brain. Disruption here can affect information processing.
2. Chromatin Remodeling and Gene Regulation: A significant number of autism genes help control the "on/off" switches for other genes, especially in the brain. When these regulators are broken, the finely tuned program of brain development can go awry.
3. Transcriptional Regulation: These genes help turn DNA instructions into RNA, a critical step in creating the proteins that build and run the brain.
There is no "autism gene."
¬∑ Combination of Factors: For most individuals, autism results from a combination of genetic susceptibility (inherited common variants) and, often, a significant de novo mutation that acts as a "second hit."

text: What you‚Äôre doing is propping up the system, not defending truth. Thousands of papers don‚Äôt guarantee independence, transparency, or quality. They don‚Äôt erase weak study design, biased funding, or selective reporting. The acetaminophen and autism research you dismiss is inconsistent and confounded, and even the authors call for stronger evidence. At the same time, the genetic narrative has been oversold for decades while environmental drivers are minimized. Parents and independent researchers have been pushing these concerns long before Trump or RFK echoed them. Acting like politicians invented these questions is just a way to discredit scrutiny. We‚Äôve seen this exact strategy with tobacco, lead, asbestos, opioids, and pesticides.. massive stacks of studies waved around while the public was told everything was safe, until the evidence finally broke through. Families don‚Äôt need a PhD in statistics to recognize when science is being used as a shield for uncertainty. Ordinary people have the right to demand better research and real accountability. What you are defending isn‚Äôt science itself, it‚Äôs the authority of institutions that have been wrong and self protective on nearly every major public health crisis of the past century.
